<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="market-sizing-with-ai">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>market-researcher</domain>
    <summary>AI-assisted TAM/SAM/SOM estimation using independent top-down and bottom-up triangulation. Document assumptions, flag divergence >2x, deliver confidence ranges not point numbers.</summary>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>market-sizing</tag>
      <tag>tam-sam-som</tag>
      <tag>triangulation</tag>
      <tag>ai-research</tag>
      <tag>estimation</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Market Sizing with AI</title>
    <summary>AI-assisted TAM/SAM/SOM estimation via top-down and bottom-up triangulation. Run both methods independently using separate Perplexity and web-search calls, document every assumption, then triangulate: if both paths agree within 2x, confidence is defensible; if not, flag the divergence and identify the assumption driving the gap. Output a structured estimate with confidence ranges, not point numbers.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>TAM/SAM/SOM estimates built from a single research path are finger-in-the-air numbers. Triangulating two independent methods — one from industry reports down, one from customer counts up — increases confidence and forces explicit assumption logging. AI tools confuse TAM, SAM, and SOM if not defined in the prompt; the structured prompt pattern in the templates eliminates this ambiguity.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Producing TAM/SAM/SOM estimates to support a go/no-go decision or investor deck</item>
        <item>Triangulating market size when no single authoritative report exists</item>
        <item>Stress-testing existing market estimates by running independent top-down and bottom-up paths</item>
        <item>Automating recurring market-size updates as part of a research cadence</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>When the investor or client requires named analyst reports (Gartner, IDC) — AI cannot substitute these</item>
        <item>Highly novel markets with less than 12 months of public data — AI extrapolates from unreliable proxies</item>
        <item>Regulated contexts (IPO prospectus, SEC filing) where every number needs traceable sourcing</item>
        <item>When the market boundary is contested — AI anchors to the most common framing without flagging ambiguity</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="triangulation-rule">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run top-down and bottom-up methods in separate agent calls; do not share intermediate results between paths before triangulation.</statement>
        <rationale>If the two paths share data during computation, they are not independent. Non-independent paths produce false convergence and inflate confidence beyond what the evidence supports.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>If both methods agree within 2x, report the median with a confidence range (low/mid/high). If they diverge beyond 2x, report both values and flag the assumption driving the gap — do not average.</statement>
        <rationale>Averaging divergent estimates creates false precision. The gap itself is a signal: it identifies the key unknown that needs primary-source resolution before the estimate is defensible.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Successful triangulation with 2x convergence">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Top-Down:
Market reports → industry size → segment → target
$100B market → 20% segment → 5% addressable = $1B TAM

Bottom-Up:
# potential customers × average revenue = TAM
100K companies × $10K/year = $1B

Triangulate: both ≈ $1B → confidence HIGH, report $1B mid with $800M-$1.2B range
        ]]></code>
        <note>Both paths yield similar numbers; the estimate is defensible and can be reported.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-tools-for-market-sizing">
      <list>
        <item>Statista AI — market reports, data (export only, no API)</item>
        <item>CB Insights — company data, trends (CSV export, useful for bottom-up)</item>
        <item>Perplexity Pro — synthesis from multiple sources (REST API)</item>
        <item>Claude/ChatGPT — calculation assistance and synthesis</item>
        <item>AlphaSense — industry research, SEC filings (partial API)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="required-checklist">
      <rule>
        <statement>Before publishing any market size estimate, verify all checklist items are complete.</statement>
        <rationale>Skipping any item — especially assumption documentation or confidence ranges — creates a false-precision artifact that reviewers cannot challenge or reproduce.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Market boundaries defined clearly (geography, customer type, minimum deal size)</item>
        <item>Multiple data sources used (minimum 2 independent sources per method)</item>
        <item>Both bottom-up and top-down estimates produced independently</item>
        <item>Every assumption documented (one line per assumption in the output)</item>
        <item>Confidence ranges included (low/mid/high), not point estimates</item>
        <item>Data recency verified — flag sources older than 12 months</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="limitations">
      <antipattern>
        <description>AI tools confuse TAM, SAM, and SOM if not defined explicitly in the prompt.</description>
        <reason>LLMs use these terms interchangeably in training data; without explicit definitions in the prompt, output will conflate them and produce inconsistent estimates.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Bottom-up estimates require accurate counts of target customers; AI will guess if no reliable dataset exists.</description>
        <reason>Treat customer count as a human-supplied input, not AI output. The agent cannot verify customer count.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Statista and CB Insights data lags 6-18 months; AI-synthesized estimates inherit that lag without disclosure.</description>
        <reason>Source recency must be verified by the agent and reported alongside the estimate; stale sources must be flagged explicitly.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Triangulation only improves confidence if the two paths are truly independent — AI often draws from the same underlying sources for both.</description>
        <reason>Instruct the agent explicitly to use different source sets for each path; verify source independence before trusting the convergence.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Currency and geography scope creep: AI frequently extends a US-market figure to global without flagging the assumption.</description>
        <reason>Geographic scope must be declared in the prompt as a hard constraint, not inferred, to prevent silent extrapolation.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="orchestrator-pattern">
      <rule>
        <statement>A Claude Sonnet agent handles the full sizing loop: receive market definition, generate separate top-down and bottom-up queries, dispatch to Perplexity or web-search, collect results, output structured estimate with confidence ranges and assumption log.</statement>
        <rationale>The structured loop prevents the most common failure: mixing data from both paths before triangulation. Explicit instruction to keep paths independent is required in the system prompt, not assumed.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Orchestrator prompt structure">
        <code lang="xml"><![CDATA[
<market_sizing_task>
  <market>Cloud-based AI research tools for knowledge workers, global, 2026</market>
  <approach>Run top-down and bottom-up independently. Do not share intermediate results between paths.</approach>
  <top_down>Find total knowledge-worker software market → isolate AI tools segment → apply addressable fraction</top_down>
  <bottom_up>Estimate target companies × seats × annual price</bottom_up>
  <output>
    - TAM, SAM, SOM with confidence range (low/mid/high)
    - Assumption log (one line per assumption)
    - Source list with access date
  </output>
</market_sizing_task>
        ]]></code>
        <note>Explicitly separates the two paths and requires assumption logging. Human reviews assumption log before estimate enters any deliverable.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="cli-and-saas-reference">
      <p>Command-line tools for market sizing:</p>
      <list>
        <item>pytrends — Google Trends demand signal proxy (pip install pytrends)</item>
        <item>serpapi — Structured search for market reports (pip install google-search-results)</item>
        <item>pandas — Tabulate and triangulate estimates (pip install pandas)</item>
        <item>anthropic SDK — Drive Claude for synthesis and calculation (pip install anthropic)</item>
      </list>
      <p>SaaS tools:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Statista — export only, agent must parse downloaded PDFs</item>
        <item>CB Insights — CSV export, company counts, funding data for bottom-up</item>
        <item>Perplexity Pro — REST API, best for synthesizing analyst commentary</item>
        <item>AlphaSense — partial API, strong for public-company disclosures and earning-call signals</item>
        <item>Exploding Topics — REST API, demand signal for emerging markets</item>
        <item>Google Trends — free, pytrends, proxy for consumer demand; not reliable for B2B</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Define market boundaries in the prompt with three constraints: geography, customer type, and minimum deal size</item>
        <item>Always run top-down and bottom-up in separate agent calls to prevent cross-contamination of reasoning</item>
        <item>Include a confidence range (low/mid/high), not a single point estimate — AI cannot produce false precision</item>
        <item>Log every assumption explicitly; reviewers need to challenge assumptions, not numbers</item>
        <item>Re-run sizing every 6 months for fast-moving markets; instruct the agent to flag stale sources (>12 months old)</item>
        <item>Cross-check AI estimates against any available public analyst commentary, even if from a different geography</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents conflate TAM and SAM without explicit definitions; define both in the system prompt.</description>
        <reason>Both definitions must be injected in the system prompt on every run; they are not preserved across sessions.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs anchor heavily on the first data point encountered; instruct the agent to collect all sources before synthesizing.</description>
        <reason>Anchoring bias from early data inflates confidence; collecting all sources before producing any number is not the default behavior.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Bottom-up paths require a customer count estimate the agent cannot verify; treat this as a human-supplied input, not AI output.</description>
        <reason>The agent cannot independently verify customer counts for a target market segment.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>"Similar market" reasoning (e.g., "CRM market is $X, so AI research tools should be Y% of that") is a hallucination risk unless sourced.</description>
        <reason>Require the agent to cite its source for any comparable market used in reasoning; prevent inference without attribution.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Models will omit the confidence range unless explicitly required in the output schema.</description>
        <reason>Point estimates invite false precision; confidence ranges must be a required field in the output schema, not an optional addition.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/triangulate.py" purpose="Claude SDK triangulator that runs two paths and flags divergence >2x"/>
      <template path="templates/market-sizing-prompt.txt" purpose="Full XML prompt template for market sizing tasks"/>
    </templates>
